Augmentation therapy with alpha-1 antitrypsin slows disease progression (
 Chapman et al., 2015; 
 McElvaney et al., 2017) and discontinuation of treatment was associated with poor health outcomes, increased number of exacerbations and hospitalizations (
 Alkins and O'Malley, 2000; 
 Sclar et al., 2012; 
 McElvaney et al., 2020). Some studies concluded that augmentation therapy is a cost-effective strategy for managing AATD patients with COPD (
 Alkins and O'Malley, 2000; 
 Sclar et al., 2012). An observational study among Spanish patients also showed that these patients experienced a significant decrease in hospitalization costs and incidence of exacerbations following the start of augmentation therapy (
 Barros-Tiz√≥n et al., 2012).
